## Context

When comparing window "before" [t−w, t−1] to window "after" [t+1, t+w], the "after"
window systematically contains more papers in a growing field: climate finance
publication volume grew roughly 15× from 1995 to 2020. This means n_after >> n_before
for most t, which biases every divergence statistic that is sample-size-sensitive.

The current pipeline sets `equal_n: true` in `config/analysis.yaml`, which subsamples
the larger window to min(n_before, n_after). This is a form of debiasing, but:
(a) it is nowhere explained in the zoo prose, (b) the user cannot see how large the
bias is, (c) dropping papers to match the smaller window loses statistical power.

This ticket adds: the theoretical treatment of the bias, and side-by-side figures
showing biased (equal_n=false) vs debiased (equal_n=true) series for a representative
set of methods so the reader can judge the bias magnitude.

## Actions

### 1. Theoretical writeup in overview.md

Add a subsection "Growing-corpus bias and equal-n debiasing" to
`content/_includes/techrep/overview.md`:

a) **Bias statement**: For a distance statistic D estimating d(P_before, P_after),
   the finite-sample estimator has variance O(1/n_before + 1/n_after). When
   n_after >> n_before, the estimator is dominated by the smaller sample. Moreover,
   many statistics (energy distance, MMD, JS divergence) have non-zero bias under
   the null that grows with |1/n_before − 1/n_after|. Cite: Gretton et al. (2012)
   for MMD bias; Pérez-Cruz (2008) for JS.

b) **Equal-n subsampling**: Subsample the larger window to min(n_before, n_after)
   before computing D. This equalizes both the variance contribution and eliminates
   the sample-size-dependent bias component. Cost: power loss proportional to the
   dropped fraction. R=3 median-of-three subsampling (annex, ticket 0083) reduces
   variance of the debiased estimator.

c) **When bias matters most**: early years (small n_before) and late years (large
   n_after, but also indexing lag shrinking n_after). Plot n_before(t) and n_after(t)
   across the full time range in a supplementary figure.

### 2. Add bias flag to compute_divergence.py

Add `--equal-n / --no-equal-n` CLI flag to `scripts/compute_divergence.py`, defaulting
to the config value. Propagate to `_iter_window_pairs` in each `_divergence_*.py`.

### 3. Produce biased and debiased output tables

In `zoo.mk`, add recipes for `tab_div_biased_{method}.csv` targets (a subset of
representative methods: S1_MMD, S2_energy, L1, G9_community) using `--no-equal-n`.
The debiased tables (`tab_div_{method}.csv`) already exist.

### 4. New dual-panel figure

Write `scripts/plot_zoo_bias_comparison.py`:
- Input: `tab_div_{method}.csv` (debiased) + `tab_div_biased_{method}.csv` (biased)
- Output: two-panel figure (or overlaid) for the representative methods
- Show both series for w=3 (lead window); shade the difference
- Also show n_before(t) and n_after(t) on a secondary axis or separate panel

Add target `content/figures/fig_zoo_bias_{method}.png` in `zoo.mk`.

### 5. Reference from per-method includes

In `content/_includes/zoo/S1_mmd.md` and `L1_js.md` (as representative of semantic
and lexical), add a note referencing the bias figure and stating that all zoo results
use the equal-n debiased estimator.

